✦ The error occurs because there is no generic build script in your package.json. Instead, the previous developers
  defined specific scripts for different purposes.


  Based on the package.json file I just read, here are the correct commands you should use:


  1. For Local Development (Recommended)
  This command builds the frontend and automatically copies the files to your Umbraco wwwroot folder. It also stays
  active and "watches" for any changes you make:
   1 npm run build:umbraco

  2. For a One-Time Development Build
  If you just want to build the files once without syncing or watching:
   1 npm run build:development


  3. For Production Build
  To generate the final, optimized files:
   1 npm run build:production

  ---


  How to fix the "npm run build" error permanently:
  If you want npm run build to work like you expected, you can add it to your package.json. Open frontend/package.json
  and update the scripts section like this:


   1 "scripts": {
   2   "build": "npm run build:production",
   3   "build:umbraco": "webpack build --env development UMBRACO=true --mode=development --progress --watch",
   4   "build:development": "webpack build --env development --mode=development --progress",
   5   "build:production": "webpack build --env production --mode=production --progress",
   6   "start": "webpack serve --env development"
   7 }


  Summary of what to do now:
   1. Make sure you are in the frontend directory.
   2. Run npm run build:umbraco.
   3. Once that finishes (it will stay running), you can start your .NET project in Visual Studio.
